}{}$CI = \sum\limits_{i = 1}^n {{{\left({{{{A_i}} \over {{A_t}}}} \right)}^2}} $\end{document}CI=∑i=1n(AiAt)2, where n is the number of patches; Ai is the size of i-th patch; and At is the total area of the species distribution. An increase in the CI means distribution fragmentation decreases (Jaeger, 2000). We chose the CI as our measure and not conventional fragmentation (Cerezo, Perelman & Robbins, 2010) because of (1) its low sensitivity to very small patches as opposed to mean patch size; (2) the monotony of its reaction to different fragmentation phases; and (3) its ability to distinguish spatial patterns.
